   <text>
      <body>
         <pb/>
         <milestone n="141" unit="page"/>
         <lb/>
         <div type="poem" rhyme="abab">
            <head>EXPOSTULATION<lb/>
               <lb/>
               <hi>and</hi>
               <lb/>
               <lb/>REPLY.<lb/>
            </head>
            <lg n="1" type="stanza">
               <l n="1" real="+ + - - - + - +">“WHY William, on that old
                                        grey stone, </l>
               <l n="2" real="+ - - + - + - +">“Thus for the length of
                                        half a day, </l>
               <l n="3" real="+ + - + - + - +">“Why William, sit you thus
                                        alone, </l>
               <l n="4">“And dream your time away? </l>
            </lg>
            <lg n="2" type="stanza">
               <l n="5" real="+ - - + - + - +" enjamb="y">“Where are your
                                        books? that light bequeath’d </l>
               <l n="6">“To beings else forlorn and blind! </l>
               <l n="7" real="+ + - + - + - +" enjamb="y">“Up! Up! and
                                        drink the spirit breath’d </l>
               <l n="8" real="- + + - - +">“From dead men to their kind.
                                   </l>
            </lg>
            <lg n="3" type="stanza">
               <l n="9" real="- + + - - + - +">“You look round on your
                                        mother earth, </l>
               <l n="10" real="- + - + - + - + -">“As if she for on
                                        purpose bore you; </l>
               <l n="11">“As if you were her first-born birth, </l>
               <l n="12" real="- + - + - + -">“And none had lived before
                                        you!”</l>
            </lg>
            <pb/>
            <milestone n="142" unit="page"/>
            <lb/>
            <lg n="4" type="stanza">
               <l n="13">One morning thus, by Esthwaite lake, </l>
               <l n="14">When life was sweet, I knew not why, </l>
               <l n="15">To me my good friend Matthew spake;</l>
               <l n="16">And thus I made reply. </l>
            </lg>
            <lg n="5" type="stanza">
               <l n="17">“The eye it cannot chuse but see, </l>
               <l n="18">“We cannot bid the ear be still; </l>
               <l n="19">“Our bodies feel, where’er they be, </l>
               <l n="20">“Against, or with our will. </l>
            </lg>
            <lg n="6" type="stanza">
               <l n="21">“Nor less I deem that there are powers, </l>
               <l n="22">“Which of themselves our minds impress, </l>
               <l n="23">“That we can feed this mind of ours, </l>
               <l n="24" real="- - + + - -">“In a wise passiveness. </l>
            </lg>
            <lg n="7" type="stanza">
               <l n="25" real="+ - - + - + - +" enjamb="y">“Think you, mid
                                        all this mighty sum </l>
               <l n="26" real="- + - + - + -">“Of things for ever
                                        speaking, </l>
               <l n="27">“That nothing of itself will come, </l>
               <l n="28" real="- + - + - + -">“But we must still be
                                        seeking? </l>
            </lg>
            <lg n="8" type="stanza">
               <l n="29">“—Then ask not wherefore, here, alone, </l>
               <l n="30">“Conversing as I may, </l>
               <l n="31">“I sit upon this old grey stone, </l>
               <l n="32">“And dream my time away.”</l>
            </lg>
         </div>
